    "creditline": "Gift of John Pierpont Morgan",
    "description": "Fragment of a linen tunic with nearly intact clavus bands with pendant medallions in-woven in wool tapestry. Bands have a red ground with polychrome figures of very stylized animals, and black borders with scrolling patterns.",
    "justification": null,
    "gallery_text": "Egyptians in the Byzantine period often decorated their plain linen garments with colorful woven wool ornaments.  Most common among these were orbiculi (roundels on the shoulders and abdomen), segmenta (ornamental squares in the same places) and clavi (vertical bands running from the inner shoulder past the breasts).  These clavi terminate in pendant ovals, and are filled with a design of stylized plant forms, fish and animals, including lions, a perpetual symbol of power and authority.",
    "label_text": "During the Byzantine period (ca. 330 \u2013 1453), Egyptians often decorated their plain linen garments with colorful, woven-wool ornaments. Most common among these were orbiculi (roundels on the shoulders and abdomen), segmenta (ornamental squares in the same places), and clavi (vertical bands running from the inner shoulders past the breasts), as seen here.",
